description.value:
Papyrus written with black ink, 6 fragments, not all from the same legal document.
Thompson's MS Catalogue: "The right-hand fragment (A) does not belong to the other fragments. It is written in a different hand. It was a document of 5 ll. only: marriage or divorce? Early Ptolemaic. The remaining fragments (B-G from the right) show remains of 6 ll. remains of a convenance (? cession) of land or buildings, with a Greek docket below B and C. These cannot be parts of the same documents: but it is possible that B is part of no. 10385 supra, while the others are part of a corresponding document, e.g. sale and cession. Instances of both such documents having a Greek docket are not unknown (e.g. Pap. Hauswaldt). Date. year 47 of Euergetes II = BC 124-3".

description.value:
Papyrus (mounted in 6 frames) written with black ink with demotic legal text on recto (10 cols., each of 24-26 ll. except the last of 19 ll.) and verso (7 cols. of varying size).
Thompson's MS Catalogue (referring to the whole papyrus): "recto: the proceedings of a native court of justice consisting of three priests with a Greek assessor in a civil suit arising out of the document no. 10575 supra. verso: copies of documents relating to the text of the recto. Date year 11 Pachons 21 of Ptolemy Philometor = BC. 170 June 23".
Here shown are cols. 3-5, 5vo-7vo (pls. 3-5, 14-16 of Thompson's edition), containing the records of the trial (cols. 3-5) and a deed of apportionment (vo).
Nos. 10575-10601 from the Siut Archive.

description.value: P. Ramesseum 18, Frame 2. Papyrus written on the recto and on the verso in hieratic script. The recto contains despatches from Nubian fortresses (the so-called Semna despatches), and P. Ramesseum 18 is part of the same papyrus as P. Ramesseum C (EA 10752); another fragment is mounted in EA 10772.2. On the verso there are magical texts, including an incantation against ghosts. The text is written in horizontal lines. This frame contains page 2. The papyrus was a full-height roll.    Gardiner refers to this page as follows: 'Two pages resembling the Semna Despacthes in both subject and form, but probably not written by the same scribe. Unhappily this papyrus has suffered even more than any other, the celluloid backing having cracked and disintegrated, and having in addition developed deep brown areas entirely obliterating the text within them. Consequently it has been necessary to employ for our reproductions [in 1955] the films made in Berlin over thirty years ago ... [this page] has four relatively well-preserved black lines, but is more difficult to read; there is a reference to the Medjay Nubians, and mention of something sent in the fourth month of summer' (Gardiner, The Ramesseum Papyri, 1955, 17).    The papyrus is part of the collection of papyri found with a bundle of pens in a chest from a plundered late 13th dynasty tomb under the Ramesseum, apparently belonging to someone like a lector priest. Two of the papyri from the chest are in the Egyptian Museum Berlin (P. Ramesseum A and D); the objects are in the Fitzwilliam Museum Cambridge and the Manchester Museum.    The papyri are very fragile, apparently due to dampness in the tomb-shaft.  This papyrus was mounted on sheets of gelatin by Hugo Ibscher.

description.value: P. Ramesseum 19, Frame 2. Papyrus written on the recto and on the verso in hieratic script. The recto contains ritual/magical texts which continue on the verso. Two of the papyri from the chest are in the Egyptian Museum Berlin (P. Ramesseum A and D); the objects are in the Fitzwilliam Museum Cambridge and the Manchester Museum. The papyrus is part of the collection of papyri found with a bundle of pens in a chest from a plundered late 13th dynasty tomb under the Ramesseum, apparently belonging to someone like a lector priest. Two of the papyri from the chest are in the Egyptian Museum Berlin (P. Ramesseum A and D); the objects are in the Fitzwilliam Museum Cambridge and the Manchester Museum.    The papyri are very fragile, apparently due to dampness in the tomb-shaft.  This papyrus was mounted on sheets of gelatin by Hugo Ibscher.

Thompson's MS Catalogue: "Mounted in eleven unnumbered frames. Provenance ? Writing. various hands and periods. several columns on both recto & verso. Contents. Frame (A). recto 5 cols. & vestiges of a previous one. a land register. verso. 21 cols. prob. a summing up of the totals of aruras on the recto. Frame (B). recto. 9 cols. list of inhabitants of houses(?). verso. 9 cols. (rougher hand). list mainly of parts of the body - often repeated. [...] list of a butcher - possibly distribution to temple officials of sacrificial animals. Frame (C). recto. 5 cols. arithmetical problems. Frame (E). recto 7 cols. list of names. cols. 1 & 2 [...] male - the rest appar. female. verso. 5 cols. accounts. Frame (F). recto 5 fragments, joined but not belonging (two mounted upside down). fragt. no. 2 - part of land register headed "The island of Pnesh year 21". etc. Date. early Roman(?). … (See Merlin record for full description)

description.value: Papyrus (three fragments: one substantial, one very small and one uninscribed). Demotic administrative text. There are two columns of text on the recto of the main fragment. The verso is blank. The papyrus is torn on both sides and at the top and the bottom, but the right-hand and upper margins are preserved. Column A consists of 7+x lines of text; column B 3 lines. There are faint traces of a washed-out text beneath this. A space of 3 cm separates the two columns. Column B begins slightly higher up the papyrus than column A. The last three lines of column A, which are quite damaged, appear to be in a different hand and deal with a different subject-matter than the first four lines. The hand of the column B is very similar, possibly identical, to that of the first part of column A .

description.value:
Papyrus (mounted in 6 frames) written with black ink with demotic legal text on recto (10 cols., each of 24-26 ll. except the last of 19 ll.) and verso (7 cols. of varying size).
Thompson's MS Catalogue (referring to the whole papyrus): "recto: the proceedings of a native court of justice consisting of three priests with a Greek assessor in a civil suit arising out of the document no. 10575 supra. verso: copies of documents relating to the text of the recto. Date year 11 Pachons 21 of Ptolemy Philometor = BC. 170 June 23".
Here shown are cols. 1-3 (pls. 1-3 of Thompson's edition), containing the records of the trial.
Nos. 10575-10601 from the Siut Archive.

description.value: P. Ramesseum 1, Frame 12. Papyrus written on the recto in hieratic script. The recto contains the literary text The Discourse of Sasobek, while on the verso there are some later accounts. The text is written in vertical columns with a horizontal line for the title. This frame contains lines Dii 1-2 and Ci 1-4. The papyrus was a full-height roll.    Gardiner describes this papyrus as follows: 'This admirably written literary text, of which the upper halves of a hundred columns are still preserved, contained a moralizing text, doubtless introduced, like the Maxims of Ptahhotpe and the Prophecies of Neferti, with a brief narrative. Dr. Barns' investigation has shown Newberry's arrangement, especially near the beginning, to be incorrect in places; he has also succeeded in finding the positions of many fragments belonging to the lower halves. Nevertheless, no less than seventy fragments remain unlocated, some of them giving several consecutive words. Hence this composition, once no doubt of great linguistic and literary importance, now represents an irreparable loss' (Gardiner, The Ramesseum Papyri, 1955, 8).    The papyrus is part of the collection of papyri found with a bundle of pens in a chest from a plundered late 13th dynasty tomb under the Ramesseum, apparently belonging to someone like a lector priest. Two of the papyri from the chest are in the Egyptian Museum Berlin (P. Ramesseum A and D); the objects are in the Fitzwilliam Museum Cambridge and the Manchester Museum.    The papyri are very fragile, apparently due to dampness in the tomb-shaft.  This papyrus was mounted on sheets of gelatin by Hugo Ibscher.

description.value: P Leiden/London, recto cols. 7-10, verso cols. 32vo-33vo. Papyrus written with blank ink; demotic text recto and verso: spells and recipes; Old Coptic glosses and Greek recitation.  On the recto are a series of spells and recipes arranged in twenty-nine columns written between ruled lines. These include spells for divination, love spells, poisons and spells of healing. On the verso are apparently discontinuous memoranda, prescriptions and short invocations.    Recto:  PDM xiv. 220-231 (col. 8/1-11): An Inquiry of the Lamp (NB: This spell begins on 10070/2, col. 6/1).  PDM xiv. 232-38 (col. 8/12-18): A 'God's Arrival'.  PDM xiv. 239-95 (col. 9/1-10/22): Vessel Inquiry of Khonsu.  PDM xiv. 295-98 (col. 10/22-35): Vessel Inquiry [to See the Bark of Pre].    Verso:  PDM xiv. 1206-18 (col. 32vo/1-13): Love Spell.  PDM xiv. 1219-27 (col. 33vo/1-9): To Cure a Fever.    The spells are typical products of the syncretistic culture of Late Antiquity.  This very late demotic papyrus was sold in two parts in Thebes, the first part  going to London and the second to Leiden, where it proved important in  deciphering the demotic script, since the text contains glosses in a mixture of  Greek and demotic characters now known as Old Coptic. The entire roll  measured some 5 m.  Thompson's MS Catalogue: "Writing on both sides. recto (horiz. fibres) 10  cols. averaging 8 1/2 x 8 in. verso (vert. fibres) 9 small cols." [regarding all  London fragments, 10070/1-3].

description.value: P. Ramesseum C, Frame 3. Papyrus written on the recto and on the verso in hieratic script. The recto contains despatches from Nubian fortresses (the so-called Semna despatches); P. Ramesseum 18 (EA 10771) is part of the same papyrus and another fragment is mounted in EA 10772.2. On the verso there are magical texts, including an incantation against ghosts, as well as a strengthening strip with accounts. These magical texts consist of similarly constructed paragraphs invoking dangerous spirits who lack some part of their body. The text is written in horizontal lines. This frame contains Despatches no. 3 (page 3, lines 1-6) and no. 4 (page 3, lines 7-14) on the recto and page 3 of the verso on the verso. The papyrus was a full-height roll.    The papyrus is part of the collection of papyri found with a bundle of pens in a chest from a plundered late 13th dynasty tomb under the Ramesseum, apparently belonging to someone like a lector priest. Two of the papyri from the chest are in the Egyptian Museum Berlin (P. Ramesseum A and D); the objects are in the Fitzwilliam Museum Cambridge and the Manchester Museum.    The papyri are very fragile, apparently due to dampness in the tomb-shaft.  This papyrus was mounted on sheets of gelatin by Hugo Ibscher.

description.value: P. Ramesseum 1, Frame D. Papyrus written on the recto in hieratic script. The recto contains the literary text The Discourse of Sasobek, while on the verso there are some later accounts. The text is written in vertical columns with a horizontal line for the title. This frame  contains sixteen fragments which appear in the  following order from top  left to bottom right: Frag. 52, Frag. 36, Frag. 39, Frag. 67, Bi 22, Bi 12 (bottom), Frag. 24, Frag. 60 (mounted upside down), part of Frag 15 (?), Frag. 30, Frag. 45, Frag. 61 (mounted upside down), one unidentified and Frag. 40. It includes also a separate wisdom text fragment (to the right of the frame) known as 'Ramesseum Wisdom Fragment', written in vertical lines. The papyrus was a full-height roll.    Gardiner describes this papyrus as follows: 'This admirably written literary text, of which the upper halves of a hundred columns are still preserved, contained a moralizing text, doubtless introduced, like the Maxims of Ptahhotpe and the Prophecies of Neferti, with a brief narrative. Dr. Barns' investigation has shown Newberry's arrangement, especially near the beginning, to be incorrect in places; he has also succeeded in finding the positions of many fragments belonging to the lower halves. Nevertheless, no less than seventy fragments remain unlocated, some of them giving several consecutive words. Hence this composition, once no doubt of great linguistic and literary importance, now represents an irreparable loss' (Gardiner, The Ramesseum Papyri, 1955, p. 8).    The papyrus is part of the collection of papyri found with a bundle of pens in a chest from a plundered late 13th dynasty tomb under the Ramesseum, apparently belonging to someone like a lector priest. Two of the papyri from the chest are in the Egyptian Museum Berlin (P. Ramesseum A and D); the objects are in the Fitzwilliam Museum Cambridge and the Manchester Museum.    The papyri are very fragile, apparently due to dampness in the tomb-shaft.  This papyrus was mounted on sheets of gelatin by Hugo Ibscher.
